{"id": "duc04-testb-23:10#30", "contents": "Caught in the middle of an economic crisis, many Brazilian factories fear they won't be able to pay their workers the mandatory year-end bonus. Some workplaces have already offered their employees products such as hammers, nails, screws, and bolts instead of the traditional cash bonus, which is equivalent to one month's wage. The head of Brazil's largest federation of trade unions, Joao Antonio Felicio, has expressed strong opposition to this idea, calling it \"completely unacceptable\" and recommending that unions reject such proposals."}
